* {{ill|Shisho|ja|史生}}
* {{ill|Shibu|ja|使部}}
* {{ill|Chokutei|ja|直丁}}

* {{ill|Ryoho|ja|陵戸}}
* {{ill|Shugo|ja|守戸}}

=== Staff of Shoryoshi ===
* {{ill|Chief (正六位上)|ja|正}}
* {{ill|Deputy (従七位下)|ja|佑}}
* {{ill|Senior Clerk (大初位上)|ja|大令史}}
* {{ill|Junior Clerk (大初位下)|ja|少令史}}
* {{ill|Tsubebe|ja|土部}} – Ritual staff for funerals.

== Meiji Government ==
In {{ill|1869|ja|明治2年}} (Meiji 2), the Shoryoryo was re-established under the {{ill|Jingi-kan|ja|神祇官}} with roles such as head, assistant, clerk, and others. The head of the Shoryoryo at the time was {{ill|Toda Tadazumi|ja|戸田忠至}}, who also served as a {{ill|Ministry of the Imperial Household|ja|宮内大丞|Ministry of the Imperial Household=Ministry of the Imperial Household|lt=Miyauchi-daiyoku}}.<ref name=ishinshi-5-478>{{cite book|author=文部省維新史料編纂事務局|title=維新史|volume=5|year=1941|pages=478|url={{NDLDC|1242382/260}}}}</ref><ref name="toike">{{cite book|和書|author=外池昇|title=天皇陵の近代史|publisher=吉川弘文館|year=2000|page=71}}</ref> During this time, the tombs of past emperors were re-evaluated, and posthumous titles were granted, such as {{ill|Emperor Kobun|ja|弘文天皇}} and {{ill|Emperor Junnin|ja|淳仁天皇}}.<ref name=ishinshi-5-478/>

In {{ill|1871|ja|明治4年}}, the Shoryoryo was merged into the {{ill|Ministry of Divinities|ja|神祇省}}. After several reorganizations, it was incorporated into the {{ill|Kyobusho|ja|教部省}} as the Shoryo Section. Later, the management was transferred to the {{ill|Imperial Household Ministry|ja|宮内省}}, where it became the Imperial Tombs Section in 1878.<ref name=toike/>

In {{ill|1886|ja|明治19年}}, the Shoryoryo was revived.<ref name=ishinshi-5-478/><ref name=toike/>

