'''Shoryoryo''' (諸陵寮) was a {{ill|government office|ja|律令制}} under the {{ill|Ministry of Ceremonies (Japan)|ja|治部省|Ministry of Ceremonies (Japan)=Ministry of Ceremonies (Japan)|lt=Ministry of Ceremonial Affairs}} during the {{ill|Ritsuryo system|ja|律令制}} in Japan. It was briefly revived in the early years of the Meiji government, abolished once, and later re-established with modifications in {{ill|1886|ja|1886年}}. Its successor, the {{ill|Archives and Mausolea Department|ja|宮内庁書陵部|1=Archives and Mausolea Department}}, currently manages imperial tombs ({{ill|Tennoryo|ja|天皇陵}}).
== Duties and History under the Ritsuryo System == The Shoryoryo was initially established as {{ill|Shoryoshi|ja|諸陵司}} (和訓: みささぎのつかさ) under the {{ill|Ritsuryo Code|ja|律令}}. In {{ill|729|ja|729年}} ({{ill|Shinki|ja|神亀}} 6/ {{ill|Tenpyo|ja|天平}} 元年), it was elevated to the status of a {{ill|ryo|ja|寮}}. Its primary duties included managing {{ill|Imperial tombs|ja|陵墓}}, conducting {{ill|funeral rites|ja|喪葬}}, and overseeing rituals for the funerals of members of the {{ill|Imperial Family|ja|皇族}}. Specifically, it managed the registries of the {{ill|Ryoho|ja|陵戸}}, who were assigned to guard the tombs. In cases of misfortune, officials were sometimes sent to console the spirits of neglected Imperial Family members, as seen in the case of {{ill|Prince Sawara|ja|早良親王}}.
