The Shoryoryo was initially established as {{ill|Shoryoshi|ja|諸陵司|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shoryoshi|qq=}} (和訓: みささぎのつかさ) under the {{ill|Ritsuryo Code|ja|律令|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ritsuryo Code|qq=}}. In {{ill|729|ja|729th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/729|qq=}} ({{ill|Shinki|ja|神亀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinki|qq=}} 6/ {{ill|Tenpyo|ja|天平|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpyo|qq=}} 元年), it was elevated to the status of a {{ill|ryo|ja|寮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/ryo|qq=}}. Its primary duties included managing {{ill|Imperial tombs|ja|陵墓|1=Japanese imperial tombs|lt=Imperial tomb|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial tombs|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese imperial tombs|qq=}}, conducting {{ill|funeral rites|ja|喪葬|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/funeral rites|qq=}}, and overseeing rituals for the funerals of members of the {{ill|Imperial Family|ja|皇族|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Family|qq=}}. Specifically, it managed the registries of the {{ill|Ryoho|ja|陵戸|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ryoho|qq=}}, who were assigned to guard the tombs. In cases of misfortune, officials were sometimes sent to console the spirits of neglected Imperial Family members, as seen in the case of {{ill|Prince Sawara|ja|早良親王|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prince Sawara|qq=}}.

