In {{ill|1869|ja||1869年|1=1869|2=ja|3=1869年|lt=Meiji 2|lt_ja=明治2年||qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1869|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 1869年}}[[Category:Years needing redirect replacements]] (Meiji 2), the Shoryoryo was re-established under the [[:en:Department of Divinities|Department of Divinities]] with roles such as head, assistant, clerk, and others. The head of the Shoryoryo at the time was {{ill|Toda Tadazumi|ja|戸田忠至|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toda Tadazumi|qq=}}, who also served as a {{ill|Ministry of the Imperial Household|ja|宮内大丞|Ministry of the Imperial Household=Ministry of the Imperial Household|lt=Miyauchi-daiyoku|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ministry of the Imperial Household|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 宮内省}}.<ref name=ishinshi-5-478>{{cite book|author=文部省維新史料編纂事務局|title=維新史|volume=5|year=1941|pages=478|url={{NDLDC|1242382/260}}}}</ref><ref name="toike">{{cite book|和書|author=外池昇|title=天皇陵の近代史|publisher=吉川弘文館|year=2000|page=71}}</ref> During this time, the tombs of past emperors were re-evaluated, and posthumous titles were granted, such as [[:en:Emperor Kōbun|Emperor Kobun]] and [[:en:Emperor Junnin|Emperor Junnin]].<ref name=ishinshi-5-478/>

In {{ill|1871|ja||1871年|1=1871|2=ja|3=1871年|lt=Meiji 4|lt_ja=明治4年||qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1871|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 1871年}}[[Category:Years needing redirect replacements]], the Shoryoryo was merged into the [[:en:Ministry of Divinities|Ministry of Divinities]]. After several reorganizations, it was incorporated into the [[:en:Ministry of Religion (Japan)|Ministry of Religion]] as the Shoryo Section. Later, the management was transferred to the [[:en:Ministry of the Imperial Household|Imperial Household Ministry]], where it became the Imperial Tombs Section in 1878.<ref name=toike/>

In {{ill|1886|ja||1886年|1=1886|2=ja|3=1886年|lt=Meiji 19|lt_ja=明治19年||qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1886|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 1886年}}[[Category:Years needing redirect replacements]], the Shoryoryo was revived.<ref name=ishinshi-5-478/><ref name=toike/>

